03969nam a22005535i 9780520963559DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209635597 a10.1515/97805209635592doi  a(DE-B1597)519078  a(OCoLC)966410507  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHV8738b.S84 2018 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a365.66708209794612231 aSufrin, Carolyn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJailcare :bFinding the Safety Net for Women behind Bars /cCarolyn Sufrin. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I -- t1. Institutional Burden to Care -- t2. Triaging the Everyday, Every Day -- t3. Cultivating Ambiguity: Normalizing Care in the Jail Clinic -- t4. The Clinic Routine: Contradictions as Care -- tPart II -- t5. Gestating Care: Incarcerated Reproduction as Participatory Practice -- t6. Reproduction and Carceral Desire -- t7. Custody as Forced and Enforced Intimacy -- t8. At Home in Jail -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThousands of pregnant women pass through our nation’s jails every year. What happens to them as they carry their pregnancies in a space of punishment? In this time when the public safety net is frayed, incarceration has become a central and racialized strategy for managing the poor. Using her ethnographic fieldwork and clinical work as an ob-gyn in a women’s jail, Carolyn Sufrin explores how jail has, paradoxically, become a place where women can find care. Focusing on the experiences of incarcerated pregnant women as well as on the practices of the jail guards and health providers who care for them, Jailcare describes the contradictory ways that care and maternal identity emerge within a punitive space presumed to be devoid of care. Sufrin argues that jail is not simply a disciplinary institution that serves to punish. Rather, when understood in the context of the poverty, addiction, violence, and racial oppression that characterize these women’s lives and their reproduction, jail can become a safety net for women on the margins of society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPregnant womenxMedical carezCaliforniazSan Francisco. 0aReproductive health serviceszCaliforniazSan Francisco. 0aWomen prisonersxMedical carezCaliforniazSan Francisco. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066755440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520963559?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520963559423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520963559/original  a978-3-11-066755-4  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-073776-9  DTL Humanities 2020b2020  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles